    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush and Gore, on the Battleground of Ideas; The Military</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jacob Koskoff letter holds Sept 2 editorial is right to criticize Dick Cheney's call to increase defense spending to cold-war-era level at time of world peace</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 2 editorial is correct to criticize Dick Cheney's argument that we must increase the defense budget because it has fallen to less than 3 percent of national output. Why, at a time of prosperity and world peace, return Pentagon spending to the level reached at the height of the cold war? That was a time when domestic programs were slashed, the budget deficit inflated and the national debt soared.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 2 editorial is correct to criticize Dick Cheney's argument that we must increase the defense budget because it has fallen to less than 3 percent of national output. Why, at a time of prosperity and world peace, return Pentagon spending to the level reached at the height of the cold war? That was a time when domestic programs were slashed, the budget deficit inflated and the national debt soared.</p>
        <p>Sacrifices were made across the board to win the cold war, and that victory should be savored with a reconsideration of investment priorities and a renewed mission for our military. As the lone superpower, we have a responsibility to fight tyranny around the world. But cold-war-era defense spending will not help us meet our challenges, at home or abroad.</p>
        <p>JACOB KOSKOFF  Brooklyn, Sept. 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
